@Node "Online Help" "ConfUMS.guide/Online Help"
@Toc "Main"

Online Help
***********

   ConfUMS features a detailed Online Help which should be able to
answer all questions concerning ConfUMS. Thus you need not read the
whole documentation. If you encounter a question while using ConfUMS
just press the @{i}Help@{ui} key and you should get the according help page.

   @{i}Attention:@{ui} The documenation file "ConfUMS.guide" must reside in a
directory which is part of AmigaGuide's path.

   @{i}Usage:@{ui}

   @{b}*@{ub} To get help concerning a part of the user interface move the mouse
     pointer over the object and press @{i}Help@{ui}. The object's window must
     be the active one to use this feature.

   @{b}*@{ub} If the mouse pointer is not over a certain object you'll get the
     help page for the active window.

   @{b}*@{ub} To get help for a menu item select it with the mouse pointer and
     press @{i}Help@{ui} while you still highlight the menu item in question.


@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "ConfUMS.guide/Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
************

   What you need to run ConfUMS:

   @{b}*@{ub} a minimum of Kickstart and Workbench 2.04

   @{b}*@{ub} a minimum of UMS 10.x should be already installed

   @{b}*@{ub} a minimum of MUI 2.0 (ConfUMS uses some features of MUI, that are
     only available in v2.0 or higher!)

   @{b}*@{ub} enough memory for MUI and UMS to run, at least 1 MB of FastRAM.

   If you have all these things ready and running, simply copy ConfUMS
(and ConfUMS.info) into your desired directory.  ConfUMS can be started
from shell and Workbench. If you want to use the online help facilities
of ConfUMS, you must copy the file @{b}ConfUMS.guide@{ub} to a directory that
also appears in the @{b}ENV:AmigaGuide/Path@{ub} variable or add its path to
that var - you will usually put it into the @{b}HELP:@{ub} or @{b}HELP:english@{ub}
directory.

   Since version 1.1 ConfUMS is completely localized: you can use this
feature if you are running Workbench 2.1 or higher.  Currently there is
only a german translation available, if you want to use it copy the
file @{b}ConfUMS.catalog@{ub} (located in the @{b}Catalogs/deutsch/@{ub}-directory of the
distribution) to @{b}Locale:Catalogs/deutsch/@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Updating" "ConfUMS.guide/Updating"
@Toc "Main"

Updating
========

   As of ConfUMS v1.2 you are able to start more than one ConfUMS on
one machine, thus allowing you to edit the configurations of different
servers at the same time.

   Unfortunately, MUI now uses different filenames to store ConfUMS'
windowsizes and -positions. If you want use you old positions with
ConfUMS v1.2 and up, you should issue the following commands in the CLI
or shell:

   @{b}rename ENV:MUI/ConfUMS.wini ENV:MUI/ConfUMS.1.wini@{ub}

   @{b}rename ENVARC:MUI/ConfUMS.wini ENVARC:MUI/ConfUMS.1.wini@{ub}

   That's all @{b}:-)@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Starting ConfUMS" "ConfUMS.guide/Starting ConfUMS"
@Toc "Main"

Starting ConfUMS
****************

   ConfUMS recognizes the following arguments which can either be
specified in the shell or also be entered as ToolTypes in @{b}ConfUMS.info@{ub}
(the icon file):

@{b}NAME@{ub}
     the user's name (or his/her alias) as specified in the UMS
     configuration.

@{b}PASSWORD@{ub}
     his/her password. You may also specify the period '.' here to have
     a login-window open on invocation with name and server accordingly
     set and the password textgadget activated. This offers a means of
     quickly logging in without having to visibly state the password
     command line argument or ToolType.

@{b}SERVER/K@{ub}
     the UMS-server to which the user wants to login. This argument is
     optional. By default, ConfUMS looks for the environmentvariable
     @{b}$UMSSERVER@{ub} or uses the server "default".

   If you don't specify user or password, ConfUMS will open a
loginwindow where you can enter these arguments.


@EndNode

@Node "Login window" "ConfUMS.guide/Login window"
@Toc "Main"

The Login Window
================

   To use ConfUMS you have to log in to an account of the UMS
messagebase.

   This can be done by supplying commandline arguments or ToolTypes (in
ConfUMS' icon). (see @{"Starting ConfUMS" Link "Starting ConfUMS"}).

   If you do not supply a username or if your login attempt is not
successful the login window will be opened.

@{i}Name@{ui}
     Use this textgadget to enter your username (or alias) in the UMS
     messagebase.

@{i}Password@{ui}
     Use this textgadget to enter the password for the account.

@{i}Server@{ui}
     Use this textgadget to enter the server to connect to.

   After the "Ok" button is pressed ConfUMS tries to login with the
supplied account name and password. If the attempt fails a requester is
opened and you can decide to change the inputs and retry. On pressing
the "Cancel" button ConfUMS closes the login-window. If you activated
this function by the menu item ReLogin (see @{"Menu" Link "Menu"}) ConfUMS will continue
to work with the previous account. Otherwise ConfUMS will terminate.


@EndNode

@Node "Configuration" "ConfUMS.guide/Configuration"
@Toc "Main"

Configuration
*************

   ConfUMS is mainly configured by @{b}ums.config@{ub}-variables, so there's a
very comfortable way of configuring ConfUMS: simply use it @{b}:-)@{ub}

   Nevertheless, ConfUMS also recognizes an environment variable, called
@{b}EDITOR@{ub} (see @{"EDITOR" Link "EDITOR"}) specifying the external editor that will be used
for multiline-edits in ConfUMS. The environment variable will be
overridden if you specify the UMS variable "ConfUMS.Editor".

   Currently there are the following @{b}ums.config@{ub}-vars that will change
the way ConfUMS behaves:


 @{" ConfUMS.CallListkind " Link "ConfUMS.CallListkind"} 
 @{" ConfUMS.ContentsQuoted " Link "ConfUMS.ContentsQuoted"} 
 @{" ConfUMS.Display " Link "ConfUMS.Display"} 
 @{" ConfUMS.Editor " Link "ConfUMS.Editor"} 
 @{" ConfUMS.ForceDelete " Link "ConfUMS.ForceDelete"} 
 @{" ConfUMS.MLStartEditor " Link "ConfUMS.MLStartEditor"} 
 @{" ConfUMS.ShowContents " Link "ConfUMS.ShowContents"} 
 @{" ConfUMS.Stack " Link "ConfUMS.Stack"} 

 @{" EDITOR " Link "EDITOR"}  which is not an UMS- but an environment-variable


@EndNode

@Node "ConfUMS.CallListkind" "ConfUMS.guide/ConfUMS.CallListkind"
@Toc "Configuration"

ConfUMS.CallListkind
====================

   This preset lets you determine multiline-variables on which you
would like ConfUMS to invoke the listkind-editor by default. It is
configured as a standard AmigaDOS-pattern (see chapter "AmigaDOS
Basics" of your OS manual for details on patterns). Each time you
doubleclick (or press @{b}Enter@{ub} on) an item covered by
@{b}ConfUMS.CallListkind@{ub}, ConfUMS will present you with the
listkind-editor instead of the multiline one.

   Example:

@{b}ConfUMS.CallListkind = "cleanex.#?"@{ub}
     calls the listkind editor for all variables whose names start with
     @{b}cleanex.@{ub}

@{b}ConfUMS.CallListkind = "expire.grouplist"@{ub}
     calls the listkind editor for the @{b}expire.grouplist@{ub}.

@{b}ConfUMS.CallListkind = "(cleanex.#?|čxpire.grouplist)"@{ub}
     combines the two above mentioned alternatives

@{b}ConfUMS.CallListkind = "~(IntuiNews.#?)"@{ub}
     defaults all but the @{b}IntuiNews.@{ub}-vars to the listkind-editor

   By default ConfUMS doesn't start the listkind-editor automatically
for any variable.


@EndNode

@Node "ConfUMS.ContentsQuoted" "ConfUMS.guide/ConfUMS.ContentsQuoted"
@Toc "Configuration"

ConfUMS.ContentsQuoted
======================

   This one lets you determine whether ConfUMS should display the
variable contents of the contents window in UMS' quoted format.

   Specifying '@{b}yes@{ub}' (case insensitive) will show the quoted format, any
other value will display the "normal" format.

   So if you do not want ConfUMS to show the contents in quoted format,
use the following line:
@{b}ConfUMS.ContentsQuoted = "yes"@{ub}

   By default, ConfUMS uses the "normal" format (@{b}ConfUMS.ContentsQuoted
= "no"@{ub}).


@EndNode

@Node "ConfUMS.Display" "ConfUMS.guide/ConfUMS.Display"
@Toc "Configuration"

ConfUMS.Display
===============

   Determines which kinds of variables will be displayed at
startup-time:

@{b}gu@{ub}
     for global uservars

@{b}lu@{ub}
     for local uservars (local to the user who has logged in to ConfUMS)

@{b}gs@{ub}
     for global servervars

@{b}ls@{ub}
     for local servervars

   Examples:

@{b}ConfUMS.Display = "gu, lu, gs, ls"@{ub}
     Show all variables at startuptime.

@{b}ConfUMS.Display = "lu, ls"@{ub}
     Show only local vars.

@{b}ConfUMS.Display = "gu, gs"@{ub}
     Show only global vars.

@{b}ConfUMS.Display = "gu, lu"@{ub}
     Show only user-vars.

   By default ConfUMS doesn't display any vars (@{b}ConfUMS.Display = ""@{ub}).


@EndNode

@Node "ConfUMS.Editor" "ConfUMS.guide/ConfUMS.Editor"
@Toc "Configuration"

ConfUMS.Editor
==============

   With this var, you can tell ConfUMS which editor should be used for
the multiline-editor. This editor must be running synchronously, it
must not detach from the CLI or Shell.

   @{i}Attention!@{ui} You should only use a standard Amiga texteditor. This is
because lines have to end with LF (@{b}$0A@{ub}). ConfUMS doesn't change your
edited text before writing it back to @{b}ums.config@{ub}. The editor must not
detach itself from the CLI, therefore most editors have to be started
with a special option.

   Examples:

@{b}ConfUMS.Editor = "GED STICKY"@{ub}
     Configuration for GoldED.

@{b}ConfUMS.Editor = "ED -sticky"@{ub}
     Configuration for CygnusEd.

@{b}ConfUMS.Editor = "TTX WAIT"@{ub}
     Configuration for TurboText.

@{b}ConfUMS.Editor = "XDME -n"@{ub}
     Configuration for XDME.

   By default, ConfUMS looks for the environmentvar called @{b}EDITOR@{ub}.

   See also @{"EDITOR" Link "EDITOR"}, @{"ConfUMS.Stack" Link "ConfUMS.Stack"}.


@EndNode

@Node "ConfUMS.ForceDelete" "ConfUMS.guide/ConfUMS.ForceDelete"
@Toc "Configuration"

ConfUMS.ForceDelete
===================

   This one lets you determine whether ConfUMS should pop up a
requester when you're about to delete a variable using @{"Delete" Link "Delete"}.

   Specifying '@{b}yes@{ub}' (case insensitive) will disable this requester, any
other entry will force your confirmation.

   So if you do not want ConfUMS to show the requester and delete the
variable immediately, use the following line:
@{b}ConfUMS.ForceDelete = "yes"@{ub}

   By default, ConfUMS displays the requester (@{b}ConfUMS.ForceDelete =
"no"@{ub}).


@EndNode

@Node "ConfUMS.MLStartEditor" "ConfUMS.guide/ConfUMS.MLStartEditor"
@Toc "Configuration"

ConfUMS.MLStartEditor
=====================

   This one lets you determine whether ConfUMS should immediately start
the texteditor when entering the multi-line editor.

   Specifying '@{b}yes@{ub}' (case insensitive) ConfUMS will start the editor,
with any other entry you have to start the editor manually using the
'Start editor' button.

   So if you want the editor start immediately, as previous ConfUMS
versions up to v1.1a did, use the following line:
@{b}ConfUMS.MLStartEditor = "yes"@{ub}

   By default, ConfUMS does not start the editor immediately
(@{b}ConfUMS.MLStartEditor = "no"@{ub}).


@EndNode

@Node "ConfUMS.ShowContents" "ConfUMS.guide/ConfUMS.ShowContents"
@Toc "Configuration"

ConfUMS.ShowContents
====================

   This one lets you determine whether ConfUMS should open the
variable-contents preview-window at startup-time.

   Specifying '@{b}yes@{ub}' (case insensitive) will bring it up, any other
entry will just open ConfUMS' main window.

   So if you want to let ConfUMS open that window, use the following
line:
@{b}ConfUMS.ShowContents = "yes"@{ub}

   By default, ConfUMS does not display the contents-window
(@{b}ConfUMS.ShowContents = "no"@{ub}).


@EndNode

@Node "ConfUMS.Stack" "ConfUMS.guide/ConfUMS.Stack"
@Toc "Configuration"

ConfUMS.Stack
=============

   @{b}ConfUMS.Stack@{ub} configures the size of the system stack that will be
passed to your desired editor (@{"ConfUMS.Editor" Link "ConfUMS.Editor"}, @{"EDITOR" Link "EDITOR"}) on execution.

   You will not need this feature unless you editor does not properly
start up from ConfUMS. Such behaviour is likely to be due to short
system stack. If you repeatedly come in for trouble when using your
editor in connection with ConfUMS, try to set @{b}ConfUMS.Stack@{ub} to a higher
value.

   The default stack size passed by ConfUMS is 16384 bytes.

   Example:

@{b}ConfUMS.Stack = "32768"@{ub}
     Will call the editor with a stack-size of 32768 bytes.


@EndNode

@Node "EDITOR" "ConfUMS.guide/EDITOR"
@Toc "Configuration"

EDITOR
======

   This is an environment-variable commonly used by Amiga applications
to specify your desired ASCII-editor. ConfUMS will fall back to this
setting for multiline-editing if you did not specify "ConfUMS.Editor"
in your UMS-configuration. The editor chosen must be running
synchronously, it must not detach from the CLI or Shell.

   @{i}Attention!@{ui} You should only use a standard Amiga texteditor. This is
because lines have to end with LF (@{b}$0A@{ub}). ConfUMS doesn't change your
edited text before writing it back to @{b}ums.config@{ub}. The editor must NOT
detach itself from the CLI, therefore most editors have to be started
with a special option.

   Environmentvars can be set using the CLI-command @{b}SetEnv@{ub}. Use @{b}Copy
ENV:EDITOR TO ENVARC:@{ub} to save your settings permanently have them
available upon the next system-startup.

   Example: @{b}SetEnv EDITOR "GED STICKY"@{ub} configures the
GoldED-quickstarter.

   See also @{"ConfUMS.Editor" Link "ConfUMS.Editor"}, @{"ConfUMS.Stack" Link "ConfUMS.Stack"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Mainwindow" "ConfUMS.guide/Mainwindow"
@Toc "Main"

ConfUMS' mainwindow
*******************

   The mainwindow of ConfUMS contains several groups of userinterface
items:


 @{" The list of variables " Link "Variables"}           displaying the desired UMS variables, as
                                   choosen by the gadgets in the display-
                                   group (see below), letting you select
                                   the entry you want to work on.

 @{" The edit-group " Link "Editgroup"}                  for starting one of the three editors to
                                   modify the selected variable

 @{" The entry-group " Link "Entrygroup"}                 for modifying the selected entry without
                                   editing its contents.

 @{" The display-group " Link "Displaygroup"}               for determining which variables shall be
                                   displayed in the variable list.

   Note that some of these items will not be available if ConfUMS is
started by a user who hasn't got sysop-status (see also @{"Security" Link "Security"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Variables" "ConfUMS.guide/Variables"
@Toc "Mainwindow"

The list of variables
=====================

   On the left side of ConfUMS' mainwindow you see a list containing
those variables in your @{b}ums.config@{ub} matching the set of variables you
configured via the checkmark-gadgets on the right.

   A 'G' in front of a varname indicates a global var: it isn't
specific to a user. If the 'G' is missing that variable is part of the
current user's local configuration (see the 'User' textgadget on the
right bottom for the current user, @{"Username" Link "Username"}).

   You can select an entry by clicking on it. If you doubleclick on the
item, the singleline- or (if the variable is not a single line)
multiline-editor will invoke (see @{"Editors" Link "Editors"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Editgroup" "ConfUMS.guide/Editgroup"
@Toc "Mainwindow"

The Editgroup
=============

   This group lets you choose an editor to change the selected
configvar. Moreover, you can name new variables here. Currently, there
are three editors available:


 @{" 'New' textgadget " Link "New"}       For naming new variables.

 @{" single line editor " Link "Singleline-editor"}                  

 @{" multi lineeditor " Link "Multiline-editor"}                 

 @{" list kind editor " Link "Listkind-editor"} 


@EndNode

@Node "New" "ConfUMS.guide/New"
@Next "Singleline-editor"
@Toc "Editgroup"

@{b}New@{ub} textgadget
--------------

   Below the editors' buttons you'll find a textgadget labeled @{b}New@{ub},
where you can enter the names of new variables you want to add. If the
entered variable already exists, the listview will be scrolled to
reveal its name which will at the same time become the selected
(highlighted) item. If the variable is new to the server's
configuration, you may then select one of the three editors to
determine its initial contents. The new variable won't be written
unless you choose "Write global" or "Write local" from ConfUMS' edit
dialog (see also @{"Editors" Link "Editors"})


@EndNode

@Node "Singleline-editor" "ConfUMS.guide/Singleline-editor"
@Next "Multiline-editor"
@Prev "New"
@Toc "Editgroup"

@{b}Single line@{ub} editor button
-------------------------

@{i}Button@{ui}
     Single line

@{i}Function@{ui}
     Brings up the "single-line-edit" dialog which lets you edit
     variables that do not contain a linefeed.

@{i}Shortcut@{ui}
     S

@{i}See also@{ui}
@{"Editors" Link "Editors"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Multiline-editor" "ConfUMS.guide/Multiline-editor"
@Next "Listkind-editor"
@Prev "Singleline-editor"
@Toc "Editgroup"

@{b}Multi line@{ub} editor button
------------------------

@{i}Button@{ui}
     Multi line

@{i}Function@{ui}
     Brings up the "multi-line-edit" dialog. Using the 'Start editor'
     button your selected texteditor will be started for modifying
     variables that may contain more than one line. You can also use
     this button the re-edit the variable contents (this has not been
     possible with ConfUMS up to version v1.1a).

     ConfUMS may also immediately start the editor when entering the
     dialog, see @{"ConfUMS.MLStartEditor" Link "ConfUMS.MLStartEditor"}.

@{i}Shortcut@{ui}
     M

@{i}See also@{ui}
@{"Editors" Link "Editors"}, @{"ConfUMS.Editor" Link "ConfUMS.Editor"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Listkind-editor" "ConfUMS.guide/Listkind-editor"
@Prev "Multiline-editor"
@Toc "Editgroup"

@{b}List kind@{ub} editor button
-----------------------

@{i}Button@{ui}
     List kind

@{i}Function@{ui}
     Brings up the "list-kind-edit" dialog which is aimed to let you
     modify variables that consist of lines in the form @{b}STRING, VALUE@{ub}.

@{i}Shortcut@{ui}
