@Node "Username" "ConfUMS.guide/Username"
@Toc "Displaygroup"

@{b}User@{ub} stringgadget
-----------------

@{i}Button@{ui}
     User textgadget

@{i}Function@{ui}
     This gadget is only available to users who have sysop-status on
     the server they're logged in to. Use this gadget to determine the
     user whose local configuration you want to modify. Simply enter
     the name or an alias of the desired user in the textgadget and
     ConfUMS will display the local variables belonging to that user if
     the corresponding checkmarks (local server/local user) are set.

     With version 11.2 or higher of UMS-Server you can also use the
     popup object right to the textgadget to select a user from the
     upcoming list.

@{i}Shortcut@{ui}
     U

@{i}See also@{ui}
@{"List of variables" Link "Variables"}, @{"local uservars" Link "Local uservars"}, @{"local servervars" Link "Local servervars"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Editors" "ConfUMS.guide/Editors"
@Toc "Main"

The editors
***********

   ConfUMS has three builtin editors - hmm, let's say two builtin
editors and the facility to call a texteditor of liking to edit
variables longer than one line.

   In all the editor dialogs, you will find the following information:

@{b}Variable@{ub}
     The name of the variable you are editing

@{b}Status@{ub}
     The distribution (local or global) and kind (server- or uservar)
     of that variable

@{b}Local to@{ub}
     The user to whose local environment the variable will be written
     when you press @{b}Write local@{ub}.

   Below the edit area of the specific editor you will always find
three buttons that are selectable depending on your user-status and the
status of the selected variable (@{"Security" Link "Security"}).

@{b}Write global@{ub}
     The changes you made are written to the global environment.

@{b}Write local@{ub}
     The changes you made are written to the local environment of the
     user stated in the textfield @{b}Local to@{ub}, see above.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     The variable will not be changed. If you were about to enter a new
     variable, the variable will not be written to your configuration.

   The following editors are available:

@{i}Singleline@{ui}
     You will be presented a textgadget where you can enter or modify
     the variable to your liking.

@{i}Multiline@{ui}
     Your favourite texteditor will be invoked presenting you with the
     contents (if any) of the variable you want to edit.  When you have
     finished editing the variable save the contents to the same file
     that the editor started with (!) and quit the editor. ConfUMS will
     only adopt your changes if you leave the filename passed to the
     external editor unchanged!

@{i}Listkind@{ui}
     The listkind editor lets you edit variables that consist of single
     or multiple lines in the form @{b}STRING, NUMBER@{ub}. (@{"Listkind" Link "Listkind"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Listkind" "ConfUMS.guide/Listkind"
@Toc "Editors"

Listkind editor
===============

   The listkindeditor is for special use with variables that only
consist of lines in the form @{b}STRING, NUMBER@{ub}, e.g. @{b}expire.grouplist@{ub}:

     expire.grouplist = "
     indigo.admin,            7
     indigo.maus,             7
     maus.hb2.Amiga,         31
     maus.hb2.Amihard,       14
     maus.hb2.Amiprog,       31
     "

   With this editor you can easily edit such vars. The editor-window
consists of the following elements:

@{i}Variablecontents-listview@{ui}
     Holding the entries of the UMS-variable and each corresponding
     value.

@{i}Textgadgets for entry and value@{ui}
     You can edit an existing entry and/or value with these gadgets or
     add new entry/value-pairs to the listview. See notes below.

@{i}Up-/down-button behind value-textgadget@{ui}
     Using these buttons you can move the active entry up and down in
     the listview.

@{i}New-Button@{ui}
     Deselects the active listview-entry (if existing) and clears the
     textgadgets allowing you to enter a new entry/value-pair.

@{i}Clone-Button@{ui}
     Simply clones the active listview-entry. This is useful if you
     want to add several entries which only differ slightly.

@{i}Delete-Button@{ui}
     Removes the active listview-entry from the listview.

@{i}Sort-Button@{ui}
     The entries in the list will be sorted. Entries that contain a
     pattern will be sorted to the end of the list.

   When you select a variable from the listview by clicking on it, the
contents of the active listview-entry will be copied to the textgadgets
below the listview. You can now change the entry and/or value, pressing
@{b}enter@{ub} will change the selected entry in the listview. Every time you
have an active entry in the listview the textgadgets correspond to that
entry.

   If you don't have an active entry in the listview and you enter an
entry and/or value and press @{b}enter@{ub} in the textgadget, a new
listview-entry will be created with
   @{b}*@{ub} a dummy value ('0') if you pressed @{b}enter@{ub} in the entry-textgadget

   @{b}*@{ub} a dummy entry ('<noname>') if you first entered something in the
     value-gadget leaving the entry-gadget blank.

   @{i}Note:@{ui} You must press @{b}Enter@{ub} in either input gadgets to have your
changes come to effect. If you select another entry or press a button
without having this acknowledged your inputs to the gadgets, your
changes will be lost.


@EndNode

@Node "Menu" "ConfUMS.guide/Menu"
@Toc "Main"

The menu
********

   ConfUMS' mainwindow also offers some functions in a pulldown menu:

   @{i}Project-menu@{ui}

@{i}Relogin...@{ui}
     Brings up the login-requester (see @{"Login window" Link "Login window"}) to let a new user
     log into ConfUMS.

@{i}About...@{ui}
     A requester will come up, giving you information about ConfUMS,
     your login and whether you have sysop-rights.

     @{i}Shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-?

@{i}Iconify@{ui}
     Will close all ConfUMS-windows and put an icon on your WorkBench
     as if you had clicked on the iconify-icon in the window-border of
     a ConfUMS-window. For further information consult the MUI-manual,
     please.

     @{i}Shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-I

@{i}Quit@{ui}
     Terminates ConfUMS.

     @{i}Shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-Q

   @{i}Variables-menu@{ui}

@{i}Rescan@{ui}
     If you think the variable listview does not match your @{b}ums.config@{ub},
     use this button to rescan the configuration and update the list.

     @{i}Shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-R

@{i}Contents@{ui}
     This item is checked if the preview-window is open. You can use
     this item do display/hide the preview-window (see also
     @{"ConfUMS.ShowContents" Link "ConfUMS.ShowContents"}).

     @{i}Shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-C

   @{i}User-menu@{ui}

@{i}Change password...@{ui}
     A requester will come up, asking you to enter a new password for
     the user entered in the user-textgadget (see @{"Username" Link "Username"}). Your
     inputs to the two textgadgets of that requester will be hidden
     (i.e. inputs will be echoed by a superscript period '@{b}*@{ub}')! The
     password is only changed if both strings match.

     @{i}Shortcut:@{ui} none


@EndNode

@Node "Security" "ConfUMS.guide/Security"
@Toc "Main"

Security
********

   ConfUMS distinguishes "normal" users and users who have
sysop-status, i.e. having the keyword @{b}Sysop@{ub} in their local variablearea.

   Generally a sysop has the privilege to modify the whole
configuration, including variables local to users other than him- or
herself.

   A normal user is just able to edit his/her local configuration -
he/she cannot modify servervars (exception: his/her password) or vars
which are global or local to another user.

   Restrictions for users without sysop-status:

   @{b}*@{ub} cannot write back global variables

   @{b}*@{ub} cannot change distribution of variables (local -> global, global
     -> local)(1)

   @{b}*@{ub} cannot delete global variables

   @{b}*@{ub} cannot change variables of other users - that's why the User
     textgadget is disabled.

   @{b}*@{ub} cannot change servervariables

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  if you want to copy a global variable to your local
environment, use the @{b}Clone@{ub} button (@{"Clone" Link "Clone"}), don't change the name of the
variable and press @{b}Write local@{ub}


@EndNode

